Text: Not gonna lie, the meeting with Gfactor on Monday left our team pretty confused.
Mainly because it was quite different to what we thought we were doing going in.
The initial problem was narrowing it down, keeping in mind the clients preferences with what we wanted to learn from the project.
After talking to some people in the other groups it seemed likely everyone felt some anxiety on where to go in their respective projects.
The meetings on zoom with the team members felt a bit smoother than last week, I have a better sense of how people operate and convey ideas.
Kiki has been great at making sure everyone gets a turn to speak in our meetings and has plenty of ideas to throw around.

Susu's strengths seems to be that she is very honest with what she's thinking, which is good because it saves a lot of time!Tzu -Rara is quiet but comes up with great ideas and puts in a lot of effort in everything she does.
I'm not sure if I have strengths, but I'll usually throw in some jokes in the zoom meetings, so my main role could be class clown.
If I time travel, I may make a decent living as a court jester in the Medieval Period.
One of the issues I have been noticing is that our egos can get the best of us when deciding what to keep and what to take out of our projects.
Although this is pretty normal, I do hope that we choose ideas based on their merits and work together to figure what we can get out as a team.
For example, I had thought that certain ideas in our proposal weren't being done anymore.
At this point I wasn't sure if I misunderstood what happened during the zoom meeting, or they were added in as people were writing their sections of the proposal.
The issue with this is if we are always adding to our project based on individual wants, we will wear ourselves too thin and may end up crying in the fetal position over the next few weeks.
I will make sure to create a summary of tasks/agreements at the end of each zoom and add this to the project management system we have set up.
This should make things much clearer.
I may also have to be a bit more vocal about keeping focused on the tasks we've set out, as opposed to constantly broadening the scope of the project.
I also know that everyone's goals are not aligned with each other, so I am trying to be sensitive to what each person wants to get out of the project.
I felt the presentation went well for us and was pretty stoked to see Tzu - Rara in office and doing her presentation there.
I know one of her goals is to get better at presenting so it is cool to see her push herself when she finds it nerve-racking to speak in public.
It was also interesting seeing the different strengths each team had and what sections of the proposal they were focused on.
I felt our general strategy was well thought out and threaded many concepts together, but lacked the granular specific details that other teams did well on.
This meant we did not really touch on specific tools and systems that we were going to use for each step of the process.
I am thinking we will have to improve on this going forward as we need to figure out how exactly we are going to carry out the ideas in the project.
This will mean breaking down our project into discrete steps with a plan on what tools/software we are going to use.
Rhys and Claire seemed pretty excited about our project proposal so hopefully they ain't gonna be disappointed with the final result.
I am confident that our team can deliver something that they will find useful, if not - I can at least bake them a loaf of bread, which they can enjoy with some salt andÂ  melted butter.
Overall
